cme@clark.net (Carl Ellison) writes:

>You can also have two private keys, one on Earth and one on Mars --
>and repeatedly encrypt a message in these keys, alternating
>e[m[e[m[e[m[e[m[ .....[x]....]]]]]]]].
>

Maybe a less expensive method would be to create an internet
mail program, one of those programs like an auto-mailer.
The user would be called CLOCK@CLOCK.COM, or somesuch.

We generate a public/private key pair for it, making sure to
allow only the machine to use the private key.

When your time sensitive decrypt program wants to know
the time, it mails CLOCK a request, and CLOCK responds
with a signed answer, including the time.

And all without rockets!


Randy Johnson
rdj@engr.engr.uark.edu

PS I bet Timex could be to convinced to open such a service :)

